issue.title: Any plan to add correct typing?
How to pre-select multiple values within a filter/facet?

labels.name: wontfix
labels.description: This will not be worked on

issue.body: Currently you can use setFilter to programmatically select a filter value like so: ```js setFilter('item_status', 'MAINSTREAM', 'any') ``` I'm using that as a workaround to 'pre-select' certain values in the filter's UI. However, if you want to do multiple, it doesn't work and only sets the last one: ```js setFilter('item_status', 'MAINSTREAM', 'any') setFilter('item_status', 'SPARE-PART', 'any') ``` So in above use case, MAINSTREAM will not be selected but SPARE-PART will. Not sure if a bug, a feature that doesn't exist or if I'm doing something wrong? But the feature I'd want is to be able to pre-select certain filters in the config, but still be able to change these afterward. # But why not use the filter in the config? Well, that filter technically works but doesn't update the UI at all. So it's not visible to the user... It's also a 'global' filter so it stays active. I tried to make sure: ```js searchQuery: { // global filters are applied on API level filters: [ { field: 'item_status', type: 'any', values: ['MAINSTREAM', 'SPARE-PART', 'STOCK-ITEM', 'MAKE-TO-ORDER', 'SPECIALS'] } ], ``` That config will apply the filters but the values in the Facet will not be checked.

issue.title: Sorting in config doesn't work and throws an error

labels.name: wontfix
labels.description: This will not be worked on

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

when I add the following to the searchConfig:

```
  searchQuery: {
    sort: [{ field: 'title', direction: 'asc' }],
```

I get the following error, even though the values are the exact same as the SortOption type

`Error: [400] Sort contains an object with more than one key: field and direction
`

Here is the SortOption type for reference
```typescript
export declare type SortOption = {
    field: string;
    direction: SortDirection;
};```

**To Reproduce**

Just add this to the searchConfig
```
  searchQuery: {
    sort: [{ field: 'id', direction: 'asc' }],
```

**Expected behavior**
All results to be sorted by the field I want. 


I know there is a component for user sorting, but that's not what I'm looking for. The user doesn't get to control the sort in our use case. This might be more of a feature request than a bug, but then it shouldn't be an option in the searchConfig.

comment.body: Yeah this a genuine bug imo or missing feature. Please don't close.

issue.title: Elasticsearch connector: Incorrect handling of falsy values
issue.body:
### Description of the bug

The elasticsearch connector incorrectly handles non true values in the search results returned.  For example if we have a boolean field called important in our index, when we return a document which has a false value we get an empty object returned.

For example the returned document would look like this:

{ premium: {} }

We would expect this to return:

{ premium: { raw: false } }

Which is the structure of data being returned for a document with a true value, for example we get

{ premium: { raw: true } }



**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:

1. Create an index with a boolean field
2. Add a document which has a false value for the boolean field
3. Return the document as a search result
4. The structure of the returned document will have an empty object 

**Expected behavior**

We would expect the field to contain the raw value of the field in all cases, rather than just truthy cases.  With the current behaviour we loose data for fields which have values of false, 0, "" etc.  


**Which backends and packages are you using:**
Backend: [Elasticsearch]
Packages: [react-search-ui, search-ui-elasticsearch-connector]

comment.body: thanks for the bug report and PR. Will try release soon.

issue.title: fix: Issue 996 - falsy values in search results
issue.body:
## Description

Update the elasticsearch connector to fix mishandled falsy values

Any field which evaluates to false is returned as an empty object. This change fixes this to return the expected { raw: field value } construct.

## List of changes

Changes the mapping of fields to check for existence rather than truth.

## Associated Github Issues

#996

comment.body: thanks! Will try get it released soon.

issue.title: Elasticsearch connector: Incorrect handling of falsy values
issue.body:
### Description of the bug

The elasticsearch connector incorrectly handles non true values in the search results returned.  For example if we have a boolean field called important in our index, when we return a document which has a false value we get an empty object returned.

For example the returned document would look like this:

{ premium: {} }

We would expect this to return:

{ premium: { raw: false } }

Which is the structure of data being returned for a document with a true value, for example we get

{ premium: { raw: true } }



**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:

1. Create an index with a boolean field
2. Add a document which has a false value for the boolean field
3. Return the document as a search result
4. The structure of the returned document will have an empty object 

**Expected behavior**

We would expect the field to contain the raw value of the field in all cases, rather than just truthy cases.  With the current behaviour we loose data for fields which have values of false, 0, "" etc.  


**Which backends and packages are you using:**
Backend: [Elasticsearch]
Packages: [react-search-ui, search-ui-elasticsearch-connector]

comment.body: I have created a PR and tests which resolve this issue.

pull_request.title: fix: Issue 996 - falsy values in search results
pull_request.body:
## Description

Update the elasticsearch connector to fix mishandled falsy values

Any field which evaluates to false is returned as an empty object. This change fixes this to return the expected { raw: field value } construct.

## List of changes

Changes the mapping of fields to check for existence rather than truth.

## Associated Github Issues

#996
